We focus here on the prevalence of infection. To clarify, an infection case refers to any dog harbouring L. infantum parasites, including those with and without canine VL symptoms. Thus, we defined infection prevalence at time t as the aggregated percentage of dogs in the latently infected, never infectious, low infectiousness and high infectiousness states, which is equivalent to calculating the proportion of dogs not in the susceptible state: 4\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
